Getting started with PFNTV¶

PFNTV (PowerFlow Network Time-series Visualization) enables Network graphs and time-series data to be linked and interactive.

In [1]:
import pfntv as pv
pv.offline()

Getting started¶

Given a standard networkx graph

In [2]:
graph, pos = pv.examples.case9.network()

that contains a dictionary (dict) of data on each node, for example

In [3]:
import json
print(json.dumps(graph.nodes(data=True)[0][1]['data'], indent=4)[:200])

{
    "power_angle": -1.4062913445977676, 
    "ramp_q": 0.0, 
    "mBase": 100.0, 
    "Qc2min": 0.0, 
    "Pg": 34.001065524379136, 
    "apf": 0.0, 
    "Qc2max": 0.0, 
    "power_mag": 34.01130969

PFNTV can create an iteractive network graph with this information visible in a separate table.

In [4]:
pv.network(graph, pos=pos, scale=2, color='kind', table=True, legend=True, width=500).plot()

The toolbar at the top has several modes.

Symbol mode actions
refresh Refreshes the visualization.
tooltip Shows the contents in the table but does not highlight the color, size, or alpha values of the graph.
hover selection Shows the table contents and will highlight a single element.
multiple selection Hightlights multiple elements but does not change the table state.
click selection The only time the table will change is on a mouse click. This is useful for inspecting larger networks where you may need to scroll the table and it would be difficult to navigate without highlighting a different element.
toggle table view Show and hide the table.
search search Hightlight a value in the table using the search string.

Hovering over the legend will highlight that categoroy of elements.

Brush zooming is available. Double-click to exit the zoom.

Plots from pandas DataFrame¶

PFNTV can also render interactive stacked area graphs and line charts from pandas DataFrames. The folllowing is a wide formatted time-series DataFrame.

In [5]:
power = pv.examples.case9.power()

pv.area(power, legend=True).plot()

Combined interaction¶

We can plot these graphs together and allow linked selection based on the names of the elements. Create the components but don't call the plot method.

In [7]:
c1 = pv.network(graph, pos=pos, scale=2, color='kind', table=False, legend=True, width=450)
c2 = pv.area(power, legend=True, width=450)

Then pass the components to the pv.plot method as a list.

In [8]:
pv.plot([ c1, c2 ])

A few different color schemes are available.

In [9]:
c1 = pv.network(graph, pos=pos, scale=2, color='kind', table=False, scheme="20b")
c2 = pv.area(power, scheme="20b")
pv.plot([ c1, c2 ])
In [10]:
c1 = pv.network(graph, pos=pos, scale=2, color='kind', table=False, scheme="20c")
c2 = pv.area(power, scheme="20c")
pv.plot([ c1, c2 ])

Other examples¶

Network, voltage, and power.

In [11]:
power = pv.examples.gridlabd.node13_power()
voltage = pv.examples.gridlabd.node13_voltage()
graph, pos = pv.examples.gridlabd.node13_network()
In [12]:
c1 = pv.network(graph, pos=pos, width=400, scheme="20b", color='kind')
c2 = pv.area(power,  width=800, scheme="20b")
c3 = pv.line(voltage, width=400, scheme="20b")
pv.plot([c2, c1, c3])
